 Drawing evidence from women’s walking songs (amaculo manihamba)—once performed while traversing vast distances to the accompaniment of the European mouth-harp (isitweletwele)—she uncovers the manifold impacts of internationally-driven transboundary environmental conservation on land, livelihoods, and local senses of place. This book links ethnomusicological research to larger themes of international development, environmental conservation, gender, and local economic access to resources. By demonstrating that development processes are essentially cultural processes and revealing how music fits within this frame, Song Walking testifies to the affective, spatial, and economic dimensions of place, while contributing to a more inclusive and culturally apposite alignment between land and environmental policies and local needs and practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEcomusicologyxSouth AfricaxMaputaland. 0aEcomusicologyzSouth AfricazMaputaland. 0aJew's harpxSocial aspectsxSouth AfricaxMaputaland. 0aJew's harpxSocial aspectszSouth AfricazMaputaland. 0aMusicxSocial aspectsxSouth AfricaxMaputaland. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszSouth AfricazMaputaland. 0aWomenxSocial life and customsxSouth AfricaxMaputaland. 0aWomenzSouth AfricazMaputalandxSocial life and customs. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aborder landscape.  aenvironmental justice.  amemory.  asoutheast Africa.  awalking songs.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226538150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226538150/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBo